From Ottoman Turkish یومروق (yumruk, “fist”), further origin unclear. Either a derivation from Proto-Turkic *yum (“round”) (see yumak, yumru) or from Proto-Turkic *yudruk (“fist”) with secondary contamination with the former. Clauson thinks it is rather derived from *yumur-, unrecorded causative of Proto-Turkic *yum- (“to close”), in the sense of "something clenched", see yum- (“to close, clench”).
Cognate to Azerbaijani yumruq (“fist”), Chagatai [script needed] (yumruq, “fist”), Turkmen ýumruk (“fist”). Compare also Old Uyghur yydrwq (yïdruq, “fist”), Karakhanid يُذْرُقْ (yuδruq, “fist”), Bashkir йоҙроҡ (yoźroq, “fist”).
Learned borrowing from Karakhanid ﻳﻨﺖ (yanut) made in the time of the Language reform, ultimately from Proto-Turkic *yan- (“to turn back”). Cognate with Uyghur يانوت (yanot), Salar yanıt.

Inherited from Ottoman Turkish یاس (yâs), ultimately from Proto-Turkic *yās (“loss, damage; shame”) (see there for cognates). The semantic development may have been influenced by unrelated Arabic يَأْس (yaʔs, “despair”), whence also the borrowing yeis.
